{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488645"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:50:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"500"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/500"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.02,0.11,0.45,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/500"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74890"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"424"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with three days of pain and swelling around his left eye. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and atopic eczema. His medications include metformin, glipizide and topical hydrocortisone PRN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, a discrete round swelling near the medial canthus of the left eye is visible (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warm compresses","Topical chloromycetin","Dacryocystorhinostomy","Incision and drainage","Intravenous flucloxacillin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has dacryocystitis. Dacryocystitis refers to inflammation of the lacrimal sac. It arises following obstruction of the nasolacrimal duct which results in pooling of tears and occasionally there is supervening infection. Common causative organisms include\u003Cem\u003E Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococci spp. \u003C/em\u003Eand rarely gram-negative bacilli such as \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen dacryocystitis is localised to the lacrimal sac it will cause a palpable painful swelling at the medial canthus as seen in this image. The condition can often be treated with \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarm compresses\u003C/strong\u003E and/or oral antibiotics. However, in this case an abscess has now developed and the white patch shows where it is pointing and about to discharge. It needs formal \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E. This is often accomplished by draining the abscess via the skin however some surgeons are increasingly performing early endoscopic, endonasal internal drainage. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor acute, uncomplicated dactocystitis \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical\u003C/strong\u003E antibiotics (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Echloromycetin) \u003C/strong\u003Eare ineffective, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003E(e.g. flucloxacillin) are unnecessary, though the latter may be used in complicated cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDacryocystorhinostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical procedure that creates a passage between the lacrimal sac and the nasal cavity and is often reserved for recurrent infections and/or chronic dacryocystitis. Giving antibiotics prior to the procedure does not influence the outcome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of dacryocystitis will respond to warm compresses or oral antibiotics."],"references":["Pinar-Sueiro S, Sota M, Lerchundi T-X, et al. Dacryocystitis: Systematic Approach to Diagnosis and Therapy. Curr Infect Dis Rep 2012;14:137-46. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22286338/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74890"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"500"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17185"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17185"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b32c1ebd-7cbf-4ba5-8ba7-4a11ee380524.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b32c1ebd-7cbf-4ba5-8ba7-4a11ee380524.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":571,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74890"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:32:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:32:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"500"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90827"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"a